<TEXT>
<P>
Half of Quarter's Mergers Are International: Cross-border deals accounted for 
the majority of the value of merger and acquisition activity in the third 
quarter, Mergers &amp; Acquisitions magazine reported. 
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies acquired 112 U.S. companies valued at $14.7 billion, and 
American firms bought 57 companies overseas with a value of $7.5 billion. The 
combined value of the cross-border purchases -- $22.2 billion -- was 52% of the 
total mergers and acquisitions value of $42.9 billion, representing 378 deals. 
In the third quarter of 1989, there were 814 deals valued at $52.8 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
